  \par
\par
I left the wooden deck and walked into the house. Shortly down the hall on the right was the door to the bathroom. My heart pounded. I didn't want to make him mad. I knocked.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"What?" he projected through the sound and echo of the shower.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"It's Audrey. Mommy said I could come in and get her eyeliner."\par
\par
  \par
\par
"Okay!" he projected again. I winced at the effort he made to project his voice. I was imposing. \par
\par
 \par
\par
I opened the door and remembered my mom's step by step instructions. Left side of the sink, second drawer down. You will see my brown eyeliner pencil.\par
\par
 \par
\par
Every particle of steam cascading around me contained the scent of my dad's aftershave. I saw his beige-orange silhouette through the blurred glass of the shower door.  \par
\par
 \par
\par
I opened the second drawer down on the left and found that it was as my mom had said. There in the drawer lie her brown eyeliner pencil.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"I am just getting mommy's eyeliner. I will leave in just a minute," I said.\par
\par
  \par
\par
I wanted to be nearer, somehow, to my dad. The scent of his aftershave awoke in me a longing. He loomed large in the shower, as if my world did not extend beyond those shower walls. He was the very end of it. He was everything. If he could love me...I could be cradled forever by this inviting scent. I would have everything I could want.\par
\par
 \par
\par
But I left the warm cave, assuring him I was leaving, so he knew I was out of his way.\par
\par
  \par
\par
Mommy was proud of me for finding the eyeliner once I stepped back onto the wooden deck. We were circled by an autumn breeze and red and orange trees on which danced freckles of white sunlight. Outside was another kind of beauty than the one inside the bathroom where my dad was taking a shower.\par
\par
  \par
\par
My mom drew three brown lines on each of my cheeks to complete my Indian girl look that included two braids and a leather-fringed dress. She asked me to hold my skirt outwards on one side while doing a curtsy as she snapped a photo. Then I stood normally as she snapped another one. She had me smile for the one, and close my mouth for the other. \par
\par
