\par
Three years later, we were not in Washington anymore. Mommy, Daddy, me, and Della had moved to California. Then to Pennsylvania, where my brother was born. Then to Texas. Texas is where we were when my mom drove us kids away from our house, and Daddy did not come with us. She took us back to Indiana, where she grew up. My grandpa gave us a small grey house on his seven-acre property. He called this place The Lucky Seven.\par
\par
  \par
\par
On a numbing cold November day, Mommy met someone kinda strange. Not someone I would not expect her to talk to much. A guy who was much younger than her... but much older than me. Tony. He was 19. Granddaddy had found him at Dukam's Center. That was where guys went who were on "probation," which meant they had done something bad.... but not bad enough to go to jail. Granddaddy had asked Tony if he wanted to help take care of the Lucky Seven. Granddaddy needed him to mow the lawn, lay a long gravel driveway, build a gazebo, put fish in the ponds down the hill, and build a swing set. There was always another project.\par
\par
  \par
\par
On that cold day, Tony was hitching a trailer to Granddaddy's Volvo right up by the electric gate. My mom saw him from the window of her house, grabbed a long rabbit fur coat from the closet, and ran down the long driveway to meet him.\par
\par
  \par
\par
"Here! Wear this!" She came closer to him and prepared to drape it on his shoulders. \par
\par
 \par
\par
He saw the coat and chuckled. "I won't wear that."\par
\par
  \par
\par
"You must be freezing! Please put it on!" \par
\par
 \par
\par
He shivered in his thin white shirt. "I aint puttin that coat on." \par
\par
 \par
\par
"You're gonna freeze out here!" She was stern.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"I don't know anyone but you that would wear that coat."\par
\par
  \par
\par
"Well, okay! You're stubborn!" She hated that she was still holding the fur coat in her hands as she walked back up to the house. She walked faster when she was angry. \par
\par
 ____________________________  \par
\par
 \par
\par
When summertime came, and Tony was someone we were all used to, I saw that he played like a kid. When twisting around and piecing together the parts of Kelsey's action figures... he got lost in his world and didn't seem to be thinking about anything else... such as his job bagging groceries down the street, or his tasks on the Lucky Seven, or the fact that he had just gotten off probation. No, he wasn't thinking about those things. He was thinking about the action figures... just like my three year old brother was.\par
\par
  \par
\par
On the grassy knoll in front of our grey house, he pitched a softball while Kelsey batted. For hours. He took Della, Kelsey, and I fishing down the hill at the large pond. He taught me how to cast the line. \par
\par
 \par
\par
When he wasn't lost in playing, he was focused on pleasing. My mom went out some nights and asked Tony to feed us, bathe us, and put us to bed. \par
\par
  \par
\par
I would not let this strange man... who was such a strange age... see me naked in the bathtub. \par
\par
  \par
\par
But I sat next to him on the bathroom floor as he splashed water on my little brother and sister. I helped him wash their hair and resolve their fights over rubber toys. \par
\par
  \par
\par
Those nights we would play Monopoly, and Tony would pass out the properties to us, like dealing cards. We didn't have to earn them. Yet this didn't keep the game from lasting for hours... and Tony would slide the game under our green paisley couch so that we could resume it the next night.\par
\par
