\par
  \par
\par
The air of the Lucky Seven smelled of everything I liked in my life. Everything that had grown to be a routine. My mom taking us to J.C. Penny's where we picked out new clothes for school while she grabbed Hawaiian-printed shorts from the clearance racks for Tony. Ordering pizza and pop on Friday nights and playing Nintendo while we ate. Going on family trips to Martin's supermarket. The way our little grey house smelled fresh when we cleaned it.\par
\par
 \par
\par
The Lucky Seven was a beautiful place to live. The gravel driveway leading to our house passed an incline of dirt and wood chips to the left, on which sat old playground equipment my grandpa had secured before we came there. An uneven and rusted jungle gym that shook when we climbed it, two wooden teeter totters, and a tall swing-set whose rubber swings hung a little too low to the ground. On the other side of our grey house, the property dipped way down into a small lake and a collection of many streams attached to it. Bridges allowed us to cross each stream. On the other side of the lake was a simple tree house we could climb up and sit on top of. \par
\par
 \par
\par
One of the best parts of this little paradise were its many trees, old enough to have grown into large and looming presences. I relished the massive collision and chaos of bending leaves as the wind passed through like an unexpected guest. \par
\par
 \par
\par
"Neat, idn't it?" Tony and Mommy sipped coffee while standing out front and watching the wind and trees collide.\par
\par
  \par
\par
"It sure is a beautiful piece of property," she said.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"God sure made this place beautiful." \par
\par
 \par
\par
Tony went to a Wednesday night Bible study during which, as my mom told us, he "spoke in tongues." He tried to talk to my mom about the Bible, but as she would tell us one day, she wasn't really interested.\par
\par
  \par
\par
Tony tried to please my mom. He always did whatever she told him. I knew it had something to do with her being older and ravishing, dressing up in red lipstick, high heels, and business suits during the week. On the weekends she piled her hair into a careless pony-tail on top of her head and wore a danskin and sweatpants.\par
\par
 \par
\par
A dynamic was at play. Tony was eager to be useful and important, part of something larger in which he could make others happy. And my mom was eager to have a continual audience of one, someone to laugh at her play-on-words jokes and her baby talk and the songs she made up about us kids. Not to mention someone who loved to play with us. \par
\par
 \par
\par
I didn't like it.\par
\par
 \par
\par
Down in the laundry room one Saturday while Tony was working a shift at Martin's, I said, "Tony goes 60 miles an hour when he drives us to school." \par
\par
 \par
\par
My mom yanked the clothing out of the dryer. Her anger came out in the way she jerked her limbs, and, alot like Tony, tightened her lips downward into thin lines. "He does?"\par
\par
 \par
\par
My mom hated speeding. I did too. Being in a car that was going too fast made me afraid I was going to die.\par
\par
 \par
\par
I heard her in the kitchen that night telling Tony that her "whole life" was in that car he drove us to school in. "Under no circumstances are you to speed. You cannot go 60 miles an hour."\par
\par
 \par
\par
"K," he said with finality, like a soldier under command.\par
\par
 \par
\par
Della and Kelsey were at that young age of trusting. They hugged and kissed Tony goodnight, let him bathe them, and loved to play the tickle game with him. Now eight years old, I did not want to love a lanky 20-year old guy with a goofy and obliging grin, who tried too hard to make my mom happy. And I didn't want him to love me either. \par
\par
 \par
\par
My mom said I could start taking the school bus. The school bus came pretty early in the morning, and Tony was in charge of waiting with me at the gate while it came. The gate was too far from the house for him to watch me from there. \par
\par
 \par
\par
Tony thought of a way to get me on his good side. And it almost worked.\par
\par
  \par
\par
"My friends and I used to skip rocks across the street right before the cars came. We tried to miss the cars but sometimes we hit them," he said.\par
\par
 \par
\par
I had butterflies. This was more thrill-seeking than I was used to. "I wanna try!!!"\par
\par
 \par
\par
He demonstrated skidding a rock low to the ground so that it bounced off the pavement several times before settling on the other side of the street.\par
\par
 \par
\par
I practiced many times while there were no cars in sight. A willing teacher, he corrected my form and arm motions until I got it right.\par
\par
  \par
\par
And then it was time to throw them near the cars.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"How about that red one!" I got excited.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"I'll get this one," said Tony. I laughed wildly, and he did too.\par
\par
 \par
\par
His rock made is safely across the street not a second before the red car whizzed by. My heart pounded at the thought that the driver saw what Tony had done.\par
\par
 \par
\par
We laughed.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"I am gonna get the blue one!" shouted. \par
\par
 \par
\par
I also managed to skid the rock across the street right before the car went by.\par
\par
  \par
\par
We did several more... and then another red car came by. My rock hit the bottom of the car and bounced off it. The driver didn't seem to notice.\par
\par
 \par
\par
Tony and I were in an uproar. \par
\par
___________________________________ \par
\par
 \par
\par
On a winter day when I was feeling particularly stubborn, I said to Mommy, "Tony taught me to skip rocks across the street when cars are coming."\par
\par
  \par
\par
My mom had a word with him. And when she did, I knew I had hurt Tony deep down. I had gone behind his back... and betrayed him. \par
\par
 \par
\par
When Kelsey and Della hugged and kissed him every night, I stood stiffly. They also said "I love you" to him, and he said it back to them. I knew I was hurting him, but I would not give in. I would not hug this man whose age made him more likely to be my older brother than my dad.\par
\par
  \par
\par
After shouting, "You are not my dad!" so many times, something snapped inside of Tony, and I became the scapegoat.\par
\par
 \par
\par
It was a winter night. He had his things packed in the back of the Suburban. He must have packed them earlier that day when I was at school. He had just told my mom he was leaving. \par
\par
 \par
\par
"You are ruining our lives!" My mom's words hit me as her mascara trailed down her cheeks inside of her tears. All five of us were gathered outside the door to our grey house, shivering.\par
\par
 \par
\par
Tony was crying too. The first time I had ever seen him cry. And he was bawling like a child. \par
\par
 \par
\par
"Tony is getting ready to leave us! No, no, Tony, don't leave!" Her abdomen heaved deeply while rhythmic cries came from her mouth. \par
\par
 \par
\par
I somehow knew, deep down, that I, an eight-year-old, didn't have the power to ruin the lives of two adults and two small children.\par
\par
 \par
\par
But they believed I did. \par
\par
 \par
\par
And Tony really was getting ready to leave. \par
\par
  \par
\par
I panicked.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"Tony, please don't leave!" I said. I started crying too. \par
\par
 \par
\par
"You are so mean to him!" my mom cried. "He can't live like this! We can't live like this!"\par
\par
 \par
\par
"He is not my dad!!! But he can still stay!" I said. "It's just that he's not my dad! That doesn't mean I hate him!"\par
\par
 \par
\par
"No, Tony, don't go!" cried Della. Kelsey was sobbing next to her.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"I can't stay here," Tony sobbed. He headed towards the Suburban.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"Quit saying that! Tony, please stay!" My mom yelled through her wailing and put on her saddest and most helpless face. \par
\par
 \par
\par
"Look what you are doing to us! To this family!" she said to me.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"I am not ruining your lives! Tony, please don't run away! I am sorry I got you into trouble! I like skipping rocks! I won't get you into trouble anymore!"\par
\par
 \par
\par
"Tony is family! He is our family! You can't treat him that way!" mom said.\par
\par
\par
"Tony! Tony!" Kelsey's sobs were getting more desperate. Tony had the Suburban door open, and the light inside made Tony less visible standing outside of it. \par
\par
 \par
\par
"Tony, I promise I will stop being mean to you! Please stay! I don't hate you! I promise, I don't hate you!"\par
\par
  \par
\par
I was not ready to say I loved him. \par
\par
  \par
\par
Somehow, within twenty minutes, the five of us were wrapped in one large hug and crying. \par
\par
 \par
\par
__________________________________________  \par
\par
 \par
\par
 \par
\par
After that night, I knew in no uncertain terms that Tony was family. We had created an unspoken pack that I would not do anything more to ruin his life with us at the Lucky Seven.\par
\par
 \par
\par
He'd been wrapped around our daily routines for too long not to be family. He was a strange family member, but a family member none the less. Tony was just too close to my age. And he wasn't blood related. I made it a practice to be the first one to run up the stairs to my attic bedroom. That way, I wouldn't have to stand there tense and awkward while everyone else kissed him goodnight and I didn't. \par
\par
 \par
\par
My mom had brought home old photographs of Tony from her recent visit to see Goldy. She set them on the kitchen table, where they remained for days. I kept returning to them because I wanted to know more about him. I wanted to know why I should love him.\par
\par
 \par
\par
How I loved to hold these photos, with no sense of time, and gaze on the young Tony. Tony, it turned out, was someone that had existed at another time and place. He was not just the wiry stranger who invaded our family.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"These are the only pictures Goldy has of Tony," said Mommy.\par
\par
 \par
\par
There were five photos.\par
\par
  \par
\par
There were Tony's grade school pictures. Kindergarten, Second grade, Fifth grade. He wore the same expression in each: meek and obliging. He smiled at the world beyond the camera as if he knew he didn't have much to offer, but what he had, he would give. His dark straight hair was sleek and parted on the side, ending in uneven jags. In one of them, his skinny arms rested on a flat surface. His glasses were the same in all three pictures: chunky, dark frames and lenses half an in thick.  \par
\par
 \par
\par
Another photo showed five-year-old Tony ripping a piece of wrapping paper off his present on Christmas morning. His right arm was flown back. Mommy stood behind my shoulder as we both looked at Tony's excited face. \par
\par
 \par
\par
"That would have been the only present Tony got at Christmas," she said. "He often got no presents at all. Tony didn't have toys to play with like you do."\par
\par
 \par
\par
That was why Tony got so lost in playing with my brother's toys.\par
\par
 \par
\par
The last picture was of Tony at age three. As small as he was, he wore the same thick glasses. A diaper bulged under his cotton pants, giving the only appearance of mass on his spindly body.\par
\par
 \par
\par
"Mommy, why is Tony wearing glasses in this picture?"\par
\par
 \par
\par
"His mom didn't care about him. She let him crawl around the house all by himself. When he was two years old, he bit into an electrical cord. The cord of a fan. He got electrocuted and that's why his eyes are crossed. It's just so sad." Tears gushed from her eyes as she nodded.\par
\par
 \par
\par
I was very sad too. The sadness was like a bubble in my heart that just got bigger and bigger as I looked at Tony in the pictures. I thought the bubble would burst and that I would start to cry. But I held it in.\par
\par
 \par
\par
I could see little Tony moving inside the still pictures. I watched him crawl towards the electrical cord with his diaper bulging out of his pants, biting innocently into the cord. I shuddered. I watched him tear open his only gift at Christmas. I wished he had more gifts to open. But I saw him so happy with the one. I saw him pose sweet and mild for his school pictures, then lift himself off the stool and walk down the school hall. Did he have any friends at school? Did he get any love when he got home?\par
\par
 \par
\par
I had a sinking feeling when I thought about his childhood.\par
\par
  \par
\par
I was very, very glad that Tony now had toys to play with. And a family at the Lucky Seven that loved him. I started being extra nice to him.\par
\par
