Granddaddy was in bed for a week pretending to due before he got out of bed and back into his daily routine and onto the Lucky Seven with more projects for Tony. \par
 \par
\par
Not much changed in our house, since Tony had already been living with us for three years before the wedding day. He had become a part of our family long before he\rquote d decided he was going to marry Mom. He continued to dive in. He coached Kelsey\rquote s basketball and little league teams. He drove me through neighborhoods as I sold Girl Scout cookies door-to-door. He packed our lunches, took us for hayrides around the Lucky Seven during fall seasons, and took us to our doctor's appointments.\par
\par
 \par
\par
My friends\rquote  fathers and stepfathers were not as young and wiry-looking as Tony. They weren\rquote t mistaken for teenagers, like Tony was. But Tony was the father I had. He made life at the Lucky Seven fun and adventurous. Over time, I forgot he was once a stranger. He was the main man in my life. He held my mom together. And that held us all together.\par
\par
  \par
\par
I didn\rquote t want him to get too carried away, though, when I began to say, \ldblquote I love you\rdblquote  and hug him goodnight. So, several months after the wedding, I said it without too much feeling.\par
\par
  \par
\par
\ldblquote G\rquote night, Tony. Love you,\rdblquote  I said, avoiding eye contact as I walked to my room.\par
\par
\ldblquote I love you too, sweetie.\rdblquote\par
